e 1:\n\nInput: nums = [4,2,5,7]\nOutput: [4,5,2,7]\nExplanation: [4,7,2,5], [2,5,4,7], [2,7,4,5] would also have been accepted.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [2,3]\nOutput: [2,3]\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n2 <= nums.length <= 2 * 104\nnums.length is even.\nHalf of the integers in nums are even.\n0 <= nums[i] <= 1000\n\n \nFollow Up: Could you solve it in-place?\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def sortArrayByParityII(self, nums: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def sortArrayByParityII(self, nums: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n        even_index = 0\n        odd_index = 1\n        n = len(nums)\n        \n        while even_index < n and odd_index < n:\n            if nums[even_index] % 2 == 0:\n                even_index += 2\n            elif nums[odd_index] % 2 == 1:\n                odd_index += 2\n            else:\n                # Swap elements at even_index and odd_index\n                nums[even_index], nums[odd_index] = nums[odd_index], nums[even_index]\n                even_index += 2\n                odd_index += 2\n        \n        return nums\n```\n\nThis solution sorts the array in-place by maintaining two pointers: one for the even indices and one for the odd indices. It iterates through the array, swapping elements when necessary to ensure that even numbers are at even indices and odd numbers are at odd indices. The process continues until all elements are correctly placed.", "estimated_date": 1539475200000}